 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/unillon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nillon</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/13/00 8:27:24 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/soj/itsme.jpg height=188 width=115></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> monks and warriors doing comparable damage from 1-59 is a myth that's gotten completely out of hand, at those levels monks do a lot more. at 60 the whole game changes with triple attack though, monks should have gotten that. <p>Nillon, level 55 Myrmidon, Brell Serilis</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/uthoricofbrell.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thoric of Brell</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/14/00 1:31:01 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> Don't agree that monks should have gotten third attack. I like having one skill that makes warriors unique. However, that being said, if it turns out third attack makes us do more or even equal damage to monks at 60, I'd advocate giving monks something to make up for that. Monks are supposed to outdamage warriors.<br>
<br>
Thoric Frosthammer<br>
Silent Redemption <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ugoatfrenesi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goat Frenesi</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Goat Under Your Foot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/16/00 3:28:45 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/goatsghetto/kam-head.gif width=87 height=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> Monks getting outdmged by warriors...totally and utterly false, atleast for the first 59 levels.<br>
<br>
Remember that flying kick constitutes ~20% of the monks overall damage.  Even if warriors have comprable weapons, monks are adding kicks going as high as the 120s.  At 55, I kick for 90+ often, self-buffed.  Warrior's normal kicks can't even begin to compare to this kind of damage output.<br>
<br>
In terms of weapons, monk weapons are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> vastly</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> superior to warrior weapons.  If you need evidence of this, look to 2h.  The best, non-hasted ratio for a warrior is 31/37 (/smile Nillon).  Monks have 3 choices (19/20, 29/30, 28/30) that don't even come off gods that are clearly superior to the 31/37.  Hell, one of the best 2hb's out there for non-monks is the rod of mourning, which was nerfed, only a 29/36 (the rod of lamentation, its replacement, is only 25/36, from what I remember).<br>
<br>
At level 60 however, triple attack does add a significant boost to warrior damage output.  However, depending on how often it kicks in , it may be just a small boost to damage.  Damage testing will need to be held between lvl 60 warriors and monks to see how significant triple attack works.<br>
<br>
Concerning rogues, we deal alot more damage when the rogue cannot bs.  However, rogues do put out more damage (double bs for 500 anyone?) when they can take advantage of their class defining skill.  I feel that this is perfectly fine, /shrug.<br>
<br>
Concerning fd pulling, I have advocated in the past about its infinite uses and its necessity to groups.  However, I find myself rarely using it at all, instead relying on level knowledge, experience, and trick of the trade.  Very simply put, when I say &quot;anyone can pull this @#%$&quot;, I am being very literal.<br>
<br>
This is the case in large groups (which I spent the majority of my time now), where I just bring in the meat and the chanters take it from there.  I pull because I know what I'm doing, fd if anything unexpected happens, and split if the chanters need a mana break, in that order.<br>
<br>
However, in small 6 person groups, I do use fd pulling to some degree, opting for varients on it, such as chaining or spell-spliting (running mobs out of agro cause they stop to cast spells).  However, I fd pull (in its purest form) as little as I can, because while your in Sebilis or Chardok (I personally avoid Karnor like the plague), the backspawn does NOT give you the luxury of time needed to properly execute a fd split.<br>
<br>
In the end however, I don't feel that FD pulling needs any sort of nerfing or change.  The FD patch made it safer for monks to pull and in its current state, is fine.  I find that FD pulling is best described as crowd control, just like a enchanter mez's, bards charm, or druids/shamans root.  These are all methods that people use to control groups of mobs.  In the case of root and Feign Death, people learned how to adapt these skills to other purposes. <p><font face="Arial" size="1"><a href="http://sr.amiga.tm/cgi-bin/members.cgi?show=Kambing">Kambing "Goat" Ebonhoof</a><br>
Master of the Whistling Hoof<br><a href="http://sr.amiga.tm">
Silent Redemption
</a><br><a href="http://www.brellserilis.net">Brell Serilis</a></font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=copeland>Copeland</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/17/00 5:43:47 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> Actually, Goat, at Nillon's level (55?) the Rod of Mourning would outdamage the Staff of Battle due to damage bonus, though only slightly.  The best non-hasted two-hander for a warrior of Nillon's level is a Mosscovered Branch, though, not the Staff of Battle.<br>
<br>
However, none of this really contradicts your point that monks get the best weapons since there are quite a few monk weapons that beat the Branch.  Even SKs and Rangers have a better two-hander ( Blood Runed Two Hander and Woodsman's Staff, respectively). <p><font color=8bb4d2 face="Garamond"><b>- Cope -</b></font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/unillon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nillon</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>GD RPers</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/18/00 3:00:50 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/soj/itsme.jpg height=188 width=115></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> how so, copeland? Has the formula changed significantly since kunark was released? The damage bonus at 55 for 2h weapons is 15, the magic number on SoB is 77, it is 73 for the RoM, in fact I was given the chance to choose between the two, I did use the mourning for a while, the proc is *very* nice, but I also consulted with some other high level warriors from other servers, by far the consensus was to use the staff of battle. if you take the better critical hits into account, I think the staff of battle outdamages the rod in pure melee, the procs, while unreliable, make it very close though. <p>Nillon, level 55 Myrmidon, Brell Serilis</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=copeland>Copeland</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/18/00 6:55:08 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> Well, Nillon, it's a judgment call.  If you completely discount the proc on the RoM then, yes, SoB (nice initials!) is slightly better.  If you do count the proc, then I think the RoM is slightly better.  <br>
<br>
However, the differences either way are so slight as to be irrelevant, so there's nothing wrong with the choice you made.<br>
<br>
Criticals are largely a non-issue.  The SoB has slightly bigger criticals slightly less often; the RoM has slightly smaller criticals slightly more often.  However, some of the folks at Paladins and Stratics have parsed several hours of continous fighting and the extra damage due to criticals is not particularly significant.  Given that, I doubt that bigger/less often vs. smaller/more often debate is going to make or break one weapon or the other.<br>
<br>
You are correct, however, that the SoB would be better if you had Furious running, since the riposte damage would be a bit higher and delay does not factor into that.  To balance that, the RoM would probably taunt slightly better since faster weapons have a decided advantage in that area.<br>
<br>
Here's some math.  I'll assume you are 55th and have around 150 STR.  If your STR is different, it's not that big a factor since it takes a lot of STR to move the average damage curve.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   SoB</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Min = 1<br>
Magic = 62<br>
~Max = (225 + 150)/100 * 31 = 116<br>
<br>
Adding in the level bonus and using the 45/50/5 rule that generally applies to fighting blues:<br>
<br>
Average Damage = 15 + (.45 * 1) + (.50 * 62) + (.05 * 116) = 52.25<br>
<br>
Average Damage Per Minute = 52.25 * 600 / 37 = 847<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   RoM</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Min = 1<br>
Magic = 58<br>
~Max = (225 + 150)/100 * 29 = 109<br>
<br>
Average Damage without proc = 15 + (.45 * 1) + (.50 * 58)   + (.05 * 109) = 49.9<br>
<br>
Average DPM without proc = 49.9 * 600 / 36 = 832<br>
<br>
Now, consider 3% proc rate and 40% resist rate.  If you think MOBs resist less often, the RoM will get better; if you think they resist more often, it will get worse.<br>
<br>
Proc damage per round = .03 * (1 - .4) * 90 = 1.6<br>
<br>
Average Damage with proc = 49.9 + 1.6 = 51.5<br>
<br>
Average DPM with proc = 51.5 * 600 / 36 = 858<br>
<br>
As for the comments of the warriors on other servers...well, two things.  <br>
<br>
First, they may know something I don't know--that is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   entirely</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> possible.  My conclusions are &quot;paper conclusions.&quot;  I'm always willing to learn more about how the game works.  So, if there's something I'm missing, I would really like to hear it.<br>
<br>
Second, they may be wrong.  There is an astonishing amount of EverMyth in this game that no one questions...usually based upon something like &quot;well, it seems to me that....&quot; or &quot;I have this gut feeling that...&quot;  Look at how many folks swore that two-handers like Skarlons were superior to dual wielded weapons before the two-hander patch.  <br>
<br>
So, the approach I take is to assume I may not be right, but also to assume that the other guy may not be either until I see some testing data.  If you have some information that would indicate the math above is wrong or fails to consider some aspect, I really want to know. <p><font color=8bb4d2 face="Garamond"><b>- Cope -</b></font></p><i>Edited by <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=copeland>Copeland</A> at: 7/18/00 5:59:06 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/udyninvifargent.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dynin Vifargent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/19/00 11:08:14 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Class envy... from a monk?</span><hr size=1> goat : FD pulling is definitely over rated<br>
